Last blood duel: MP3 players against cell phones
We will recommend how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can phone.
From this it is clear that it is better to buy only the phone.
Nevertheless, there are many reasons why an independent reader should be obtained.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the needs of the future owner.
Perhaps you would hardly buy an expensive high-quality turntable to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
First of all these musical products do not come out as LP and from the qualitative point of view for this there is not even an objective reason.
If, however, your shelves are crowded with hard-rock, jazz or blues vinyls, you probably dream of such a turntable.
It also works with portable music, i.e. compressed music or simply in MP3 format.
Here too there are price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend 8,000 crowns on a reader, as well as a fan of Pink Floyd perhaps hardly digests the headphones from twenty crowns of the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The decision is the life of the batteries.
Some high-quality music players can do much more than just read music, but they don't do cell phones by accident.
There is no other current device as universal as the mobile phone.
Next to the primary functions, call and text, can read music and video, record both and have a camera, sometimes better sometimes worse and maybe can also navigate.
And if we consider smartphones and handhelds you will also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It's a little miracle because no refrigerator can make the grill and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of cell phones also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile phone and before the indicator on the screen will require the charger.
And reading music consumes a lot of energy.
Few mobile phones can read music for more than twelve hours, usually, and much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest players) are much more effective.
As for uncountable cheap mobile phones that can last for more than a few hours.
If you still add, from time to time, some calls, get to work for safety another charger, this also applies to the most expensive devices.
But you won't have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst ones last at least 9 hours with continuous functionality with a charge.
A further problem arises when you download music into your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited portion of devices have a USB universal port and not all of them can be connected to the computer without special software.
Certainly the music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few memory readers are able to do it without adapter for minicards that are not used in mobile phones.
Readers, except for a few exceptions (Ipod) do not need any special software.
Just fill the device with music via USB from the computer.
Most mobile phones and readers create themselves a multimedia library ordered according to the names of the interpreters, the name of the album, genre or according to the user's classification.
Some devices reproduce only the tree structure of folders, similar to the Explorer tool in Windows, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobile phones can do more.
When choosing a particular device, you should be particularly interested in battery strength, memory capacity, quality and type of audio outputs and clearly ease of use.
If you need music especially from the background and if you listen to it every day only briefly on the tram you just need a mobile phone that reads MP3.
This now succeeds, clearly to any cell phone.
You don't have to deal too much with what formats your mobile phone or reader recognizes.
MP3 players support them all, the global majority of the music you get will be in this format.
In addition to this format that belongs to the most popular ones, most devices support music in WMA format.
There is less AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods).
The best mobile phones also allow, for example, to buy music online.
Simply visit, through the mobile internet network, the corresponding pages of the operator (or another provider) and buy the song or album.
This same service could already be a valid argument to buy a mobile-reader.
Unfortunately the offer of the operators is poor and is usually limited only to hits of the moment of the radio.
Prices aren't really very low.
But it is generally assumed that this mode of sale of music (whether via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their phones behind them.
Anyone who wants to listen to a little bit of a rumble in their pocket while the MP3 player is forgotten at home.
But it also depends on this, if you always carry the headphones or at least the wireless earphone.
If not, you can use the built-in player that almost every mobile phone, but only a small part of MP3 players, it has.
Perhaps the greatest advantage of mobile-readers will, for many, be the price.
The cheapest ones normally cost less than 3,000 crowns.
For 3 and 4 thousand crowns you will already buy a very dignified walkman.
Usually, however, you will be limited by the absence of an input for the common headphones.
The best mobile phones and from the technical point of view more equipped and also with the 3.5 mm socket for the common headphones, cost up to 15 thousand crowns.
Instead, the advantage of readers is, in addition to others, easy handling.
The simplest ones are not necessarily cheaper (see our choice) and anyone really can handle them.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of handling once with the common stereo or maybe the turntable, is obvious.
There is no danger of accidentally bumping into the launch of the mobile internet network and consequently a giant bill for data transmission.
Which device to take
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have an interchangeable memory card slot (type M2, microSD etc.).
Also with regard to the purchase of the respective card, you are part of the 2 000 crowns.
But be careful
The basic models support only cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones make it even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, take Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you don't have to spend more than 1 100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, preferably take specialized mobile phones - walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices feature individual MP3 buttons and the convenience of the service so it approaches the same MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson has made more progress in this area, which mobile phones of the Walkman line have the same scale of use as MP3 players sold separately.
The MP3 players of the above brands provide you with the same service and price category up to 4 000 crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery strength (commonly 15 hours, in principle up to 35 hours).
The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
Perhaps the mobile market in the Czech Republic is mature enough and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Here, however, something is missing - a virtual operator who obliges traditional operators to lower the price.
Maybe it won't be for a long time.
We have already written on Mobil.cz many times about the fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive in Europe.
At the end of the day, ČTÚ also confirmed this, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regularising roaming charges, perhaps a paradoxical situation will arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How can prices in the Czech Republic remain so high vis-à-vis Europe?
The answer is simple, lacks the competition that would really like to start the confrontation.
Maybe it sounds crazy, even here we have three mobile networks and highly over 100% coverage.
Instead, mobile phone operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense it often emphasizes also the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, who in the past has sometimes expressed that there is no room for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with his own network doesn't have many possibilities anymore. (Moreover, perhaps it would be difficult to find other frequencies now).
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry into the market of virtual operators has led to a significant fall in prices, to which traditional operators would have to react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks like Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile into the market, similar voices resonated in Britain as we did.
However, it has been shown that there is a place for operators of this kind and that they can really be successful.
At the end of the day, for example, we must not go very far.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year this operator managed to win over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking lies the Penta financial group to which in the Czech Republic belongs among other things U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to be able to actually work, he needs a lot less customers than a traditional operator.
They do not carry with them, i.e. relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So virtual operators in the world usually show up at low cost, offering cheap calls and text messages, which is often in balance with the supply of the narrowest services
So for example Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers SMS that cost at least half as much as its competitors.
But as shown by the example of Mobilking in Poland can be a pretty good move even the bet on a group-target not small.
This operator focuses so to speak specifically on men.
"True men choose the mobile operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company that produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept can be said by us as in Poland.
The press spokesman for Vodafone Miroslav Čepický doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover, from the point of view of services it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic no possibility, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is ever an operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but negotiations in the Czech Republic do not have much expectations.
Mobilking will be switched on in the other countries of our area," he said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz Jana Studničková, the press spokesman for the Penta financial group.
It has thus indirectly confirmed that current operators in the Czech Republic are not very much in favour of this thinking.
Rather on the contrary, they try to do everything to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
For some time now, it has not hidden its interest in starting a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already managed to move forward in negotiations with some of them," says Pavel Kaidl, spokesperson for the group.
So maybe better times will come.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator will probably have to have it by the end of the year.
For now, however, there is an impenetrable wall of silence around its creation.
"We do not believe that in the Czech market there is space for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has addressed us," he mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň of the press section of Telefònika O2.
The specific nature of the Czech market also applies to other operators.
Press spokesperson T-Mobil Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with statement O2: "For now we have not noticed any viable and beneficial commercial project for both, on which it is possible to continue to build" .
He adds: "In the T-Mobil network a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this moment we will have had to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it might be possible to consider it on the horizon."
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on achieving its 3G license requests.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators, especially in the context of sharing costs and infrastructure.
Let us consider this, from the point of view of customers, the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet."
Competent authorities - with their accomplices
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in profit.
Then why facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The annoyances around the U:fon creation testify that when operators care about one thing they can row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure was on ČTÚ during the period of creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This testifies to public access information from ČTÚ's web pages.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for which not accepting the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The environment of competition in the mobile market has been little improved beyond all with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place on him and especially on his high demands services."
Of the attitude of mobile operators, however, it is surprising that the Czech regulatory authorities are completely uninterested.
It is not just the attitude of ČTÚ that unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Great Britain and other developed countries - has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
That belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, has taken its typical position with regard to all the problems.
"The virtual operator's entry into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract for the rental of the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator had been realized.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers has probably not been interesting enough for traditional operators," said Kristián Chalupa,of the Section for External Relations ÚOHS, in the answer to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators is perhaps not surprising.
On the other hand, on the part of the office which must defend the interests of consumers and, on the other hand, take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, it is more than a delicate affair.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "At abroad where virtual operators commonly work, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services."
But of course the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of ÚOHS.
Truly shocking throughout the situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence arises alone.
Just as the identical price of petrol for all petrol stations is certainly the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section found no signs of anti-competitive behavior regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so it does not have a corresponding greater responsibility for its conduct on the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be missing from the telecoms regulator," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many controversial points .
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications are the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
On such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - the network operator's agreement is always necessary for the creation of a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator has - in the end logically - the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it has to be dominant.
But even if we do not accept this argument, for ÚOHS it should be a minimum warning that three mobile operators are proceeding in such a strangely similar way.
At the same time, complaints from interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that very similar obstacles are encountered during negotiations with all operators.
Downloading the responsibility to ČTÚ in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which ÚOHS keeps himself out of the whole thing.
We have already seen this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to promote the expansion of ČTÚ's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recent update of the Telecommunications Act, despite the fact that many experts expected the situation to improve.
This fact the representatives of ÚOHS must know more than well, but perhaps their interests lie elsewhere.
It can be done when no one looks
While without us noticing it remains the functioning of such pseudo-virtual operators, some of which even exist in the Czech mobile networks.
These companies publish their own price lists for mobile phone services, but they are only partially public.
It's usually the companies that deal with multilevel marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only pre-established people.
The magic lies in the fact that the company vis-à-vis the operator appears as a classic corporate customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer he then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar pre-sale.
"If the cases you are talking about, of which we will be interested, were to be in breach of the contractual conditions, and could result in the conclusion of cooperation with that company," Martina Kemrová answered the question in question.
But it is unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 companies mentioned, thousands of customers can be involved.
No operator defends himself from such an attitude at the same time.
From the activity of these companies they derive a not indifferent profit and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - they are not damaged in any way with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it as the usual customers of mobile operators "
But that should be a strange little bit at ČTÚ.
In addition, another question arises for ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why are they blocking the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that ÚOHS has strong enough rights to unmask similar activities, and if it does not wish to do so, it will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators who have no idea of all this and that their trading conditions prohibit it.
When we're not more expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a significant fall in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where operators were born, traditional operators tried more or less to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were practically identical - too small a market, too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
But in the developed countries in these very cases the regulatory bodies have intervened in defence not of mobile operators but of their customers.
Both with formal measures and with non-formal pressure, then we came to the creation of the first virtual operator and others followed him.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory organs launch from one to the other all the time like a hot potato.
In our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity in skills in these cases is more than convenient.
But let's not throw in the towel.
If the background information is right and the virtual operator will really soon appear to us, the Czech mobile market will start again.
If one of the operators had consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only hardly ÚOHS could remain impassive to the refusal (discrimination) of the other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented in a solemn way the new recordings of the national anthem "Kde domov můj" on the occasion of the Day of Recognition of the Czech State.
The new recording of the anthem was made by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - solo with male or female voice, choir pitch and instrumental edition.
The song is under the direction of Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the anthem reviews are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz website you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song one of the most beautiful hymns.
Already earlier he said on the radio "Český rozhlas" that he chose specifically to sing variants alone, the singers with the young voices most representative, which are expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried to take care that both and also the choir, have the clear diction, that the text is well understandable, that they are in harmony," he said.
Then the national anthem will celebrate next year the 175th anniversary.
The song "Kde domov můj" was played for the first time in 1834 on the stage of the Stavovskéh divadlo in the original work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl accompanied by the music of František Škroupa.
He gained popularity and people spontaneously made it his own.
The first verse of the song after the founding of the Czech Slavic Republic in 1918 then became the natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the birth of the autonomous Czech Republic.
