In a separate city, pride and trials of a black life
Hidden in the theme park on the outskirts of Orlando, a few miles from the splendor, the noise, the huge, lies the quiet city where the pride and complications of the African-American experience enter into life.
Eatonville, the first black city incorporated into the country and the birthplace of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as he described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools and no prisons."
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to show their respect to Hurston, the most famous writer of Harlem Renaissance.
Yet in many ways, the city that he described - and that makes tourists stop including it in the Florida tourist guide produced by the Depression-era Federal Writers' Project - remains a separate place.
It is as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural black people in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, who "knowing so little about us, he doesn't know what he's missing."
Even now, in a year where a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, has been called for an opening speech on race, many here remain wary of the outsider's gaze.
"We are very cautious about how our story is told," said 59-year-old Hortense Jones, a lifetime resident and member of the oldest church in the city.
"It has to be right."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It is both a historical model of black power taking and a community of almost 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a literary center but also an example in the shadow of the oaks of the rural culture of the southern blacks - sometimes disdained, sometimes rewarded - born from American slavery.
Not surprisingly, residents here are both proud and protective.
And the concern about Eatonville's image really began with Zora, whom everyone here calls Hurston.
She presented the world to her hometown through sincere books, rich in dialect, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of Florida's guide transformed the city, just outside the Rout 17, a road that runs through the often forgotten center of Florida into a scenery from black history and human drama
Low as a bass drum in life and literature, Hurston brought readers to the store owned by the first mayor of Eatonville, Joe Clarke, and then diverted to more private areas.
"Out of the street on the left," he wrote, "is the modern public school, brown with white finishes, with its well-kept gardens and courtyards, which Howard Miller always looked after, thinking he could just read and write."
She also mentioned the widow's new husband, Dash, and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and anything that suits the passing rooms."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, second weddings and sex.
Clearly this wasn't Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
"Zora said it what it was like," said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson's girls who Hurston captures by quoting men who sing gross songs about their beauty.
He adds: "Some people don't like it."
Hurston is still remembered here as a vibrant eccentric who frequently returned from his family who moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembers that when Hurston came into the city, he usually arrived without warning in a triumphant Chevrolt, smoking and wearing pants in a city that even today boasts of dignified clothing.
Many people were fascinated, says Mr. Franklin, while others were grinning.
"People were always very happy to see Zora," said Mr. Franklin.
But, he added, swinging in his chair on the patio on the back overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books had gone out of print.
Together with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in a plaqueless grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no big memorial ceremonies, and no big conference.
"I don't think they understand his contribution to the world or his legacy to everyone," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
A change occurred in the 1980s.
Orange County officers wanted to place a five-lane highway across the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the main two-lane road.
The expansion of Orlando has already pushed Interstate 4 across the western edge of the city.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, in addition to other things, had put an end to its idyllic isolation of the community
In the 1950 ' s, the battle over racial mix brought hatred to the community's doorstep.
"During that time, a group of white boys came and threw oranges and things at the people sitting on one side," says Mr. Franklin.
"We actually had a girl who was killed by that one once.
They threw a watermelon out of a car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston made a request to the Supreme Court for forced integration, calling his decision in Brown against the school office "an insult rather than an honor for my race."
Residents now say that the desegregation of schools, despite having been positive in some respects, dilutes the cohesion of Eatonville and endangers the confidence of its young people.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember this - you were hugging your teacher in the morning, hugging your teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, Ella Dinkins' daughter and the executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a non-profit group.
This lasted, he added, until the teachers and students came from the same place.
"You didn't hug your white teacher because your white teacher... I mean, there's a cultural division there," said Mrs. Nathiri.
Civil rights, however, helped and created space for many other Zora Neale Hurstons - black writer, actress and artist who overcame prejudices, as she did, with joyful self-confidence and lines like: "How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I just don't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker began a long journey to the Hurston tomb without a plaque and began to fight for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, Robert E. Hemenway's acclaimed Hurston biography hit the bookshelves and re-introduced it into the American canon.
The highway project arrived just as his most famous daughter had again turned the spotlight.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning a festival dedicated to Hurston in 1988 to show what could ruin the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the memorial.
Many years later, the state pulled back from its project on the road.
"The five lanes of the resurrected highway brought what one would call high speed, a real pride for the city," said Ms. Nathiri.
Mrs. Boyd makes it easier: "Zora saved Eatonville."
Victory over the highway project helped change the image that the city has of itself.
Those from outside cities like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began to come to church here in 1993, began to appear in large numbers, and the residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville joined the public historical register in 1998.
A new one-storey bookcase (called Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a refurbished and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly of Florida: only six miles from downtown Orlando, it can give the feeling of a secondary road in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1980s of 1800s.
(It's 90 percent black today.)
The outsiders who come to look for the story of Eatonville, for its meaning, are often still treated with caution.
A permit requested in advance is required for most of the interviews, to some things - such as the murals on the oldest church in Eatonville, painted by a white man, who show black men in the fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Ms. Jones, a fat teacher, with a weakness for bright red, still fear that their island community will be misunderstood.
Yet, as soon as the Hurston festival expanded, a high level of city pride has also emerged.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston saw his entire race: beautiful, problems and everything, neither better, nor worse and proud, creative, great worker, silly and confused like other races and ethnic groups in America.
