Drivers of alcoholism will have to install "Alcocock"
The Ministry of the Interior requires that drivers with three administrative penalties for excessive blood alcohol, install in their car the system that prevents the driving of the vehicle in a state of drunkenness or if it does not blow in the appropriate device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the General Public Prosecutor's Office, according to which it will be a pilot project lasting one year.
The aim of this project is to reintegrate the driver, since this will have to attend a rehabilitation course on the road.
This initiative, in addition to the General Public Prosecutor's Office for Road Safety, will be attended by the General Directorate of Traffic (DGT) and the Technical Institute for the Safety of the Automobile (FITSA).
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of drivers reported more than once per DUI then return to drive the car.
Alcoholock would avoid this, because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the rate of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting up if the driver does not blow, or when a higher concentration of alcohol is detected than that allowed.
The cost is more than 1000 euros and would be borne by the sanctioned.
In this respect, a study carried out in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such devices can reduce up to 65% of the infringements committed during the first year of introduction.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to stop these behaviours before they become criminal offences.
And to facilitate its development, since legal reform can be carried out on an ordinary basis, and, no doubt, the reform necessary for criminal proceedings would require an organic law.
However, the device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been introduced experimentally in some industrial and public vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative by the PSOE in which it intends to install this system in school buses, as has already been done in France.
