Talking in your sleep
Some children talk during the night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the previous day, but to those children who speak while they are asleep.
The first time that happens, at most you get a scare, but it doesn't really matter.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquy.
It occurs with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you have been told that you had spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur in a very sporadic way (once in life, for example associated with a high fever episode) or with a greater regularity (each day, once a week, once in the month ...), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason to explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are episodes related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, nocturnal fears, night enuresis (to pee in bed), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily so.
As mentioned above, it can be associated with very high fever stages, stress or overexcitement situations.
In any case, it is a phenomenon that has not yet been studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks in a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (screaming, shouting, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be appropriate to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to check if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as a vent to the situation.
We have said that this is a benign alteration, so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (e.g. when coupled with insomnia or stress).
What can be done, however, is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the baby too much before I go to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid programs or television series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
