Meeting - Blood is sure again
The Héma-Québec celebrated yesterday the tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, as the Héma-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, seriously shaken by the scandal of the infected blood in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus in the 1980s.
In the face of such a tragedy and the protests of the population, the Government of Canada conducted in February 1994 a public investigation, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to spread recommendations to prevent the recurrence of such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was late in drawing up a report, some provinces set up a committee to design a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide Québec and Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, just 38% of people said they still trusted the donation system in Québec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood collection and field research over the following years, we have regained public confidence," he explains before saying proudly that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the population of Quebec had already trusted Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary is nevertheless convinced that "confidence is something extremely fragile."
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of mad cow, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells the one who has been in the presidency since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we absolutely didn't know if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
One was therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which when one has doubts and could achieve a serious disease, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, is taken measures of exclusion.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980 was refused.
Now, for some years now, it has been shown that this disease is undoubtedly transmitted through infected blood.
This incident has shown us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999 a much more efficient technique appeared on the market for the detection of HIV: nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow to recognize directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against it, on which instead the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, i.e. from the moment the person contracted the disease to the one where the first viruses can be detected in the blood through our techniques, explains the specialist.
That period could be reduced to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and of not being able to identify them has thus decreased significantly.
These improvements have considerably reduced the risk of contracting AIDS by a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving infected blood from the HIV virus.
"In other words, this means that you will need to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted by transfusion is found.
I believe that today we can feel calm in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, says the head of the management of Héma-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the Western Nile virus, is transmitted in blood by an insect.
We must be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before pointing out that in addition to having safe resources, the Héma-Québec must also provide enough.
"The needs increase as the population grows older.
As treatment for aggressive cancer, patients often need red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for the number of donors, which on average represents only 3% of the inhabitants of Québec acceptable as donors."
However, all healthy people who are 18 years of age and who meet the eligibility criteria may donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is widespread, they will be rejected for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we manage to maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
Cases of shortage are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this group of donors as they grow older and can no longer make donations.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold it and encourage them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so hectic that it's hard to find an hour to give blood," said Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of USD 297 million, the Héma-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissues, of which bone transplants, ocular cardiac valves and skin that is used almost exclusively for serious burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being deposited at the Héma-Québec which manages the only public bank of cord blood in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, abounds blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the insertion in the bank of our thousandth cordon blood sample and we expect to take more than a thousand each year.
You should start proposing them for transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary who describes this practice of collecting cordon blood as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot have access to them," as Héma-Québec does not have the means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Québec.
