Operation - rescue for Wall Street - Dialogue between Republicans and Democrats
The Bush administration and Congress leaders, representatives of the Republican and Democratic deployment, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest rescue-financing plan after the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US $700 billion plan, which aims to put a stop to the financial crisis that has been hanging on Wall Street for months, still needs to be ratified by the two chambers of Congress.
It provides in particular: checks on its effective implementation by elected leaders, new mechanisms guaranteeing the reimbursement of public money, new provisions to contain the number of houses foreclosed for failure to pay payments, as well as a right of inspection on remuneration paid to managers of protected companies.
The US Treasury Secretary, Henry Paulson, the President of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, yesterday, at the end of a two-day negotiation marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an effective market agreement," said the representative of the Bush administration, Henry Paulson.
"Every decision has been taken in such a way as to safeguard the economy and the American people from the current crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"It is the crucial point: if we had not acted in this way, inestimable disappointments and disturbances would have poured into the daily lives of the Americans," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The conclusion of the negotiations was marked by concerns about the impact of a new bankruptcy on investors.
The time allowed was the opening of the markets this morning.
Together with the negotiations later, the two candidates for the U.S. presidential elections were rather in favour of the agreement, without, however, avoiding expressing their discontent with the adoption of extreme solutions.
The Democratic Senator Barack Obama deserves to have added a number of provisions to the agreement, in particular that which will allow owners to maintain their domicile and that relating to remuneration for managers of undertakings covered by the State.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of others, there is nothing to rejoice about.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the screen of the American TV.
Interviewed on another channel to see if he will vote in favour of the plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I would like to analyze the details, but I hope so."
"As I read it, it is something that we all have to digest and that will allow us to move forward."
The option of non-intervention is simply unacceptable," he said.
The 700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers' money doubtful credits, assets at risk and unsold by US financial institutions.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis due to the outbreak of a real estate bubble that led first to the collapse of mortgage loans at risk (muti), and then extend to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAAs) and lead to the freezing of liquidity and the heeling of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republicans in charge who blew up the first draft of an agreement last week.
It seems to have come out of that dead end since the Democrats agreed that the "toxic" assets of some companies in difficulty will only be protected by the government rather than purchased.
In order to meet everyone in Congress, a provision has been added that, if the government were to cope with losses over the next five years due to this programme, it could impose new taxes in order to maintain its balance.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first sum of 250 billion, to which 100 billion more can be added if the President considers it necessary.
The payment of 350 billion should be ratified by a further vote of Congress.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get shares in the protected companies that will benefit him dividends in case of profit and that he will be able to resell when the waters have calmed down.
According to the plan, the federal government will have the possibility to delay the foreclosure procedures relating to real estate loans and to set limits on the remuneration and the departure allowances paid to the managers of the companies involved.
Starting today, the architects of the plan would like to submit it to the vote of the House of Representatives, and to the vote of the Senate on Wednesday.
