What was produced in Zuschlag's invoice factory & partners?
On 8 October, the hearing of the criminal trial against János Zuschlag and his associates will be discussed.
The politician and his associates are accused of repeated commercial fraud committed in the context of a criminal association that has caused considerable damage, and other crimes, including forgery of documents.
According to the Public Prosecutor's Office, the money obtained from invitations to tender was used by them for private purposes, and they have often certified the execution of the activities through false invoices.
The state and municipal money, in total 65 million guilders, ended up in part in the coffers of the organization Fiatal Baloldal, in part in the pockets of some people.
According to the method, announced by the investigating authorities, they have withdrawn the money obtained from invitations to tender on the basis of invoices for non-existent transactions and the associations have never fulfilled their obligations.
According to the accused act, most of the invoices were false.
To make them, the invoice blocks were purchased at the Józsefváros market, the circular stamps instead were manufactured in Kiskunhalas.
And to decide on which companies to issue invoices, it was established, among other things, during the trip between the hills above the Balaton where János Zuschlag had sent István Lados.
According to his confession he had to choose pensions and restaurants.
He asked for an invoice for the consumptions, on the model of these then were prepared the invoices to be forwarded to the competition notices, among others, to those of the Ministry of Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs and the Municipality of Budapest.
A large part of these are the work of István Lados and András
One of the choices of the "journey studies" of Lados was a brewery.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and its members in 2003, the restaurant provided meals for a group of 90 people from the Biztos Pont Egyptian Association.
So many people, however, according to the restaurateur, would not all enter the club together.
Similarly, the invoice issued in summer 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, hereinafter referred to as Egypt at Harmadik Évezredért, is full of formal errors and content.
A guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj has only three rooms, more than 10 people could not stay overnight, however in the invoice there were 130 guests.
