The web 2.0 speaks only of collaboration, of intentionally leaving traces behind us and exploiting the communication channels at our disposal and while the size of these changes for each individual, the substance is the same: to show ourselves.
A young average can create profiles in multiple community pages, from Facebook to Xanga, can connect them with other services such as Twitter or last.fm that lists his musical tastes, all these can insert them in systems like FriendFeed or Blip.fm, can also write blogs on which his most recent photo galleries appear automatically stored on Flickr or on Picasa.
In the meantime we read of many exemplary cases from which it is clear that the girl, seeing the series of photos taken in the morning from the common tour of friends, gets to know easily with those who spent the night her perfidious boyfriend or a company can fire an employee because he has written a sincere opinion on the company summit: one thing is sure, the concept of private life has now completely reconsidered.
Those who live an online life make sure to show themselves and so we can formulate the fundamental thesis that hides behind the behavior of young people.
Those who want to hide something or just want to avoid Google's monopoly can do so (for example by starting with Scroogle using Google's search system but at the same time does not voluntarily leave traces).
There are not a few people who do not intentionally register on community pages not to be found, Google's online applications, from text processing to image management and news collection, can be replaced with alternative versions not linked to huge server parks and that do not make up our best profile so far.
Public opinion doesn't even wait so much in secret for the moment when Google pulls its claws out.
Currently, the company with its 156 billion dollars worth is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca Cola (110 billion dollars), advertising space AdWords/AdSense threatens the revenues of advertising agencies, the services introduced in record time instead cause big problems not only to Microsoft but also to numerous software development firms.
However, critical observers, alongside all this, find alarming points: the company summit for example completely rejected the employee protest after doubling the company's asylum fee, considered the repeated daily catering to be too expensive, but all this diminishes in view of the fact that in 2006 Google bowed the head to the Chinese government and under their agreement the company will filter out all the results that offend the good taste and interests of the Chinese regime.
An internal rule of the company seems to be not to advertise a new service in advance but only when it is usable, but one thing is certain, that the predictable problems of the coming months and years will move the world at one point: while some believe that the project of scanning and storing Google's books and magazines will assume such proportions that the company will soon be faced with the American Supreme Court, others are afraid of the Health system, in fact in this we can create our own health profile with our reports, doctors and problems.
The fact that Google is building a given genetic base can offer good material to the next generation of science fiction writers, the Scroogled tale of the famous Cory Doctorow describes the future with Orwellian accents, in which a man with Google data can be approached alarmingly.
