Smart machine mimics hornet flight
What could be the best way to develop anti-collision technologies than to imitate the sensors of the obstacles found in nature?
Like bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan the hornets gave the initial strategic inspiration to Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of anti-collision systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic robot, a robotic minicar equipped with the properties of bees, with the ultimate aim of creating a system capable of removing all collisions.
Flying bees form their own personal oval space that really resembles our protective shield - explained Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technologies and research and development.
Important is the role of the bee view, capable of a 300 degree view in each direction.
The engineers drew on the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the bee view.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately transforms it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, changes direction immediately turning the wheels of the measure necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance manoeuvre, in a different way from the current system, takes place in a completely instinctive way.
"If this were not the case, the robot car would not be able to react quickly to avoid collisions," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the car robot project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damaging and inner layer of the protective shield, in which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees the deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of wheel steering.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to scan other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lithium polymer batteries, lighter and with high energy density, which means that their lifespan is greater than those of lithium ions.
According to Andoh, the instantity of the intelligent reaction is important, not data processing or even less the ability to store them.
This robot needs to process some inputs in seconds and react.
There is no need to memorize them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuvering data, so it uses only a few dozen Kb memory.
There is no need for a memory of gigabytes or megabytes.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, they predict at Nissan, within 10 years can be installed on the standard vehicles.
Further possibilities of application can be represented by the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system which avoiding obstacles on the road leads to destination.
