Mr Járóka, according to the press office of the Fidesz EP Parliamentary Group, pointed out, in addition to discrimination in recruitment, that Roma were first excluded from the labour market because of their low schooling.
"Most young Roma are not entitled to study at average level and as a result of poor quality primary education only a small number of them can achieve a higher degree of study."
Járóka also stressed, as a fundamental human right, the key role of education in enforcing human rights.
Investing in the education of Roma children can mean strengthening the economy of the member states of the European Union.
She felt that these links should be made more aware in the wider context of Roma and non-Roma.
In fact, the sooner a Roma school starts, the more its chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market grow; through taxes paid for income and consumption contribute to the nation's budget.
"The Roma's right to European citizenship must guarantee their right to quality education and the elimination of low-level and secreted schools" - said Lívia Járóka.
According to the Member, the European Union's objective and action union is needed to speed up the process of desegregation of schools and for this reason it is of fundamental importance to respect the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives.
"The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be interrupted, we must give the Roma children the opportunities provided by the democratic space so that they can contribute as full citizens of the future of Europe," asked Járóka.
In the sign of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities" to be guaranteed for all, the aim of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities organized every year, from the Berlin meeting last year is to ensure a unique forum to promote the objectives of anti-discrimination and equal opportunities set at State and European level.
