Listening to loud music for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing injury.
This is reported by the European Commission, which in a press release published in Brussels cites the opinion of the EU's Scientific Committee on Emerging and Newly Identifyed Health Risks (Crsseri) published today.
"This scientific opinion shows that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable musical devices weekly for more than one hour a day, keeping the apparatus at high volume, risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and high-hearing mobile phones can unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably," says Meglena Kuneva.
"There is a clear risk from the scientific findings," continues the EU manager, "and we must react quickly.
What is more, we need to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems, in the light of this scientific opinion, in order to ensure that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the large use of portable musical instruments and the increased number of young people exposed to noise from them.
"Scientists - the EU executive concludes - confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine together with Member States and stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and related equipment."
At present, there is already a European safety standard which limits the noise level of portable musical equipment to 100 dB, but concerns are growing about the hearing damage that may result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to limit much of this damage by using solutions such as reducing noise levels and duration of exposure to noise.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee points out that users of portable musical equipment if they listen to high volume (more than 89 decibels) music for only 5 hours per week exceed the current limits on maximum permitted noise at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk permanent loss of hearing capacity after a period of 5 years.
This would cover 5-10% of users of such devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
