The Elite in Danger
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the $700 billion rescue plan launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
The New York Times of yesterday confirms this by informing us that the current crisis is breaking the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old soul East Coast, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, instead, conservative, hostile to "those of Washington" and the world of finance, strong especially in the States of the Centre and the South.
The soul, in fact, which has become powerfully alive with the vow of which I said at the beginning.
However, this just mentioned is just an example of the changes, of the great changes, which the current economic earthquake perhaps announces or already lets us see: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps even here alone.
Both in the US and in Europe the crisis seems to function as an accelerator of incubation phenomena for a long time that in the new climate solidify and finally come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the updating, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category State-Sovereignty in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which, yes, have close ties with foreign countries, but which first of all see very much involved the budgets of people and families living in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and those families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems essentially out of the question or not to have much to say: the clear proof is given by the European Union which, as usual, divided between different interests and between different state strategies cannot decide any common political line.
And so it is from the government of every single state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all the provision of funds: since when you get to the straits it is only the States that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things back together.
They also possess the necessary means and the right to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, under certain circumstances, which probably no market and no international organization can ever have to a similar extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the statue-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we have now entered the realm of the net, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future will have to reckon to an increasing extent with those very little immaterial things that are the water, the crops, the oil.
All things that, look a bit, can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth but are however absolutely linked to a limited space, to a territory.
So those who are sovereign of it certainly have several more cards than those who are not, to those who have the misfortune of living in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second news, however, that foreshadows a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis appears to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the demand of someone who can take hold of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaders, especially economic ones, proved to be so inadequate and full of shadowy areas.
And together something even deeper and in a certain sense disturbing: a discredit, an insuffering, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in a growing number of countries of the West.
In other words, there seems to be more and more the conviction that before their actions are the same ideas as the social elites so far, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall meaning of the term, to have done their time and to be increasingly foreign to the opinions of the majorities.
The demand for leadership, in short, subterraneanally feeds a ramified but powerful movement of delegitimation of the ruling classes and traditional political structures, which manifests itself in the sudden "revolt" electoral or in the sudden turns of collective moods of these last and very recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of Labour consensus in Great Britain, to the rebellion of American Congressmen against Bush (and perhaps also the victory of the right in Italy has something to do with it).
We have the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats would say someone, they are increasingly struggling to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not taking shape in the deep strata of Western societies and that the economic crisis invigorates, increases, potentially agitates to an extent.
In the face of all this, speaking of a "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes open is certainly not at all.
