It is as if a friend, an acquaintance with whom we shared a piece of the road and so many emotions were missing," observes the director of Nuovo Cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago earned Tornatore the Oscar prize and the Grand Prix of the Cannes jury, and that told the poetry of a provincial hall and the nostalgia for a way of living the lost cinema maybe forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of exhibitors, speak clearly: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed their doors, and to pay for the greater heat are mainly the rooms in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 less in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinema monosala lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to demonstrate that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new multisala cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally," notes Paolo Protti, president of Anec," it is useful that new structures are built but it should be ensured the survival of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its visitors are willing to move into multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of funds for exhibitors: the government's previous debt is about €10 million.
It is shameful, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the Government does not comply with existing laws.
To support the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros per year would be needed."
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about closures, decided to run to the shelters with the signing of a protocol between the Municipality and Anec, the first of this type in Italy, to protect and promote monosala cinemas both in the historic center and on the outskirts.
Among the rules provided there are tax relief measures in favour of managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic zone and will have special rates for parking and in some parking spaces.
"It's an initiative that I like," says Giuseppe Tornatore,"and I hope that other cities follow the example of Bologna by putting in place other measures.
It is certain, however, that to counter the overpower of multiplexes, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, because today the audience is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important for me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradise," which I had already been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto or Quirinale in via Nazionale now closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, not to see the billboards blackened by dust I turn to the other side."
Links between politics and 'ndrangheta arrested mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to align the City's choices with the interests of the cosca Piromalli."
The accusations that the judges of the Calabria Anti-Mafia Directorate address to the mayor and deputy mayor of Gioia Tauro Giorgio Dal Torrione and Rosario Schiavone, and to the mayor of Rosarno Carlo Martelli, arrested this morning for external competition in Mafia association, are heavy.
In handcuffs also Gioacchino Piromalli, the elderly mediator between the clan and the public administrations, and his nephew lawyer, homonymous of the boss, already convicted by association for criminals of the mafia, sentenced to compensate 10 million euros.
"In disregard of any legal and moral norms, as well as common sense," the prosecutors wrote, the two local administrations had expressed their willingness to pay advice to lawyer Piromalli.
"It would have been granted to the cosca - the judges write - to enter officially inside the municipalities facilitating the possibilities, already huge, of control and direction of the public administration."
The president of the Calabrian regional council, Agazio Loiero, does not hide that there are many "collusions between local authorities and organized crime" in his region: "There are areas where the mafia intensity is stronger than in others, where collusion is almost inevitable.
But there are many local politicians who resist the pressures of the 'ndrangheta, heroes who keep themselves clean."
The arrests this morning follow those of last July with which the police announced that they had beheaded the Piromalli cosca.
Since the end of April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro was dissolved but already in 1991, and always due to alleged conditioning between organized crime and local administration, the local politicians had been relieved from the task of administering the municipality.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, mayor of UoC at the time of the dissolution, had been elected head of a center-right coalition, after the ballot of May 2006.
He shouted at the scandal when the Prefecture ordered the dissolution of the city council.
He called into question the then Deputy Minister of the Interior Marco Minniti, accusing him of having planned everything for a political question, but the judges, in the arrest order signed this morning, explain that the cosca Piromalli had even come to ask for the variation of the A3 project.
From the environmental intercepts ordered against Dal Torrione, write the pm, it emerged "the willingness to marry the needs of an entrepreneur, representative of a wider group known to be close to the Piromalli, uniting the choices of the public administration to the interests of the cosca."
When the energy comes from the waves now the bigs fall into the field
It is an exterminated deposit, which occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface and is now being discovered by the world's major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which they have put their eyes, and now they try to put their hands, colossal like Chevron.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for now a hundred years and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, the research intensified.
When the price of oil dropped, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was set aside, but now environmental demands and the new increase in oil give impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be covered by ocean wave power plants.
This amount would be twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power stations.
And there would also be currents and tides.
Colossus on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the understanding was announced it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years later, betting on marine energy is getting more and more and among these companies that have always been devoted to traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies - said the spokesman of a company associated with the US oil giant at the Wall Street Journal economic newspaper - and is considering cooperating with us."
This cooperation concerns obtaining a permit from the US Committee on Energy, which is necessary to start a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
This is not a small sign, especially considering that in Alaska the US continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has launched a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron there are the Verdant Power Inc. of New York and the Ocean Power of New Jersey to walk the road of energy coming from the sea and the sums invested so far, although not known in detail, indicate, according to observers, an increasing interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts talk about a technology still in its early days, also because marine energy does not escape all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, installations such as the Portuguese one or some in Scotland are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, technologies with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the choices are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The wave thrust, which causes the buoys to move up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
Pressure spins a turbine that in turn powers a generator.
Electricity is sent to shore through submarine cables.
For now there are four plants of this type in the process of design, waiting only for federal approval and part of the energy could serve for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a shopping mall and a parking lot using six submarine turbines in the East River of New York.
The movement of the water when there are tides turns the blades of the turbines, creating a rotating movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary permissions to take advantage of the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say at the Institute for the Research of Electricity, deserves at this moment the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than the wind, the sun or the waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is precisely on the energy of the tides that states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, together with others overlooking the coast, have already invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and planned investments up to 35 million for 2009.
